6. Why does this work?

The stack always keeps elements in strictly decreasing order.

When processing a number:

Remove all smaller or equal elements because they can never be the next greater element.
The first larger element on the stack is the answer.

Traversing the array twice ensures every element also considers values before it (after wrapping around).

Each element is:

pushed once per traversal
popped at most once

So the algorithm remains O(n).

7. Java Code
class Solution {
    public int[] nextGreaterElements(int[] nums) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] ans = new int[n];
        Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

        for (int i = 2 * n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {

            int idx = i % n;

            while (!stack.isEmpty() && stack.peek() <= nums[idx]) {
                stack.pop();
            }

            if (i < n) {
                ans[idx] = stack.isEmpty() ? -1 : stack.peek();
            }

            stack.push(nums[idx]);
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
8. Time Complexity

Each element is pushed and popped at most once (per effective processing).

Overall:

O(n)
9. Space Complexity

The stack stores at most n elements.

O(n)
10. Important Interview Note

The only difference from Next Greater Element I is that the array is circular.

Instead of physically duplicating the array, iterate from 2*n - 1 to 0 and access elements using i % n. The first traversal prepares future greater elements, and the second traversal fills the answers.

11. One-line Note for Interviews

Use a Monotonic Decreasing Stack and traverse the array twice (from 2*n-1 to 0) using i % n to simulate a circular array. Pop all smaller or equal elements, and the remaining top is the next greater element. 🚀
